SIMPLE: precedent
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Precedent
<hw>Pre*ced"ent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>praecedens</ets>, <ets>-entis</ets>, p. pr. of
<ets>praecedere</ets>: cf. F. <ets>pr⟦eacute⟧c⟦eacute⟧dent</ets>. See
<er>Precede</er>.]</ety> <def>Going before; anterior; preceding;
antecedent; <as>as, <ex>precedent</ex> services</as>.</def>
<au>Shak.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>precedent</xex> injury.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Condition precedent</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a
condition which precede the vesting of an estate, or the accruing of a
right.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Precedent</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Precedent
<hw>Prec"e*dent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Something done or said that may serve as an example to authorize a
subsequent act of the same kind; an authoritative example.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Examples for cases can but direct as <qex>precedents</qex>
only.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A preceding circumstance or condition; an
antecedent; hence, a prognostic; a token; a sign.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A rough draught of a writing which precedes a
finished copy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A judicial decision which serves as
a rule for future determinations in similar or analogous cases; an
authority to be followed in courts of justice; forms of proceeding to be
followed in similar cases.</def> <rj><au>Wharton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Example; antecedent.</syn> <usage> --
<er>Precedent</er>, <er>Example</er>. An <xex>example</xex> in a similar
case which may serve as a rule or guide, but has no authority out of
itself. A <xex>precedent</xex> is something which comes down to us from
the past with the sanction of usage and of common consent. We quote
<xex>examples</xex> in literature, and <xex>precedents</xex> in
law.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Precedented</ent>⟦br⟧
